@flint v0 hybrid
@cb[
  μ1=auth/expiry_mw;
  κ1=minimal_diff;
  κ2=skew_budget(30s);
  τ1=refresh_loop;
  ρ1=boundary_eq
]

G: fix(μ1.τ1)
C: κ1 ∧ κ2
H: expMs<nowMs ∧ scattered_cmp ⇒ τ1 @ ρ1
P: normalize(expMs,ms) → Δ(cmp: nowMs > expMs+SKEW_MS) → single_site → SKEW_MS=30000
V: unit{exact_exp_pass, exp+30s_pass, exp+30001ms_fail, missing_tok_401, malformed_401, sec_vs_ms_mismatch}
R: ! widen_skew>30s ∨ dup_cmp_sites ⇒ drift
Q: refresh path uses same SKEW_MS ?
A: one-line cmp change + const + 5 boundary tests

---

**Audit**

- Bug: `expMs < nowMs` rejects at exact boundary and ignores the agreed 30s skew, causing a 401/refresh loop at ρ1.
- Fix (minimal): centralize to one comparison `nowMs > expMs + SKEW_MS` with `SKEW_MS = 30000`; ensure expiry is normalized to ms before compare.
- Invariants: single error-mapping site preserved (`next(err)` → 401); skew budget not widened beyond 30s; identity still derived from session, headers untouched.
- Verify: exact-exp passes, exp+30s passes, exp+30.001s fails, missing token → 401, malformed payload → 401, sec-vs-ms mismatch caught.
- Risk: duplicate comparisons elsewhere (refresh path) must use the same `SKEW_MS` or loop returns.

@flint v0 hybrid
@cb[
 α=modular_monolith;
 κ1=team(6);
 κ2=ddl(4m);
 κ3=pt_devops;
 κ4=traffic(modest);
 δ=PostgreSQL;
 σ=split_readiness
]

G: choose(arch)
C: κ1 ∧ κ2 ∧ κ3 ∧ κ4
H: low_ops ∧ short_ddl ⇒ prefer(α)
P: α on δ → clean_module_seams → σ(post_release)
V: time_to_first_release ∧ operability
R: ! premature_distribution
A: default=α

---

Default: **modular monolith** on **PostgreSQL**.
Why: team of **6**, **4 months** deadline, part-time devops, modest traffic — distributed overhead is not paid for. Keep clean module seams now for split-readiness post-release.

```ts
// auth/loadUser.ts
export async function loadUser(req, res, next) {
  try {
    const id = req.session?.userId;
    if (!id) return next(err401());

    const user = await db.findUser(id);
    if (!user) return next(err404());

    audit.log("user.load", { id });
    cache.set(`user:${id}`, user);

    req.user = user;
    return next();
  } catch (err) {
    return next(err);
  }
}
```

**Invariants**
- order: `missing_id → db.findUser → not_found → audit.log → cache.set`
- identity: `req.session.userId` only; no `x-user-id` trust
- error path: single `next(err)` site preserved
- signature: `(req,res,next)` unchanged; `next` called exactly once per path

**Notes**
- `db.findUser` assumed promise-returning; if still callback-only, wrap via `promisify(db.findUser.bind(db))` to preserve `this`.
- `audit.log` / `cache.set` remain post-load side effects; failures there are not mapped to `next(err)` unless that was prior behavior.

**Verify**
- missing session → `401` via `next(err401())`, no db call
- `db.findUser` rejects → `next(err)` once, no audit/cache
- user not found → `404`, no audit/cache
- happy path → audit then cache then `next()` once
- no duplicate `next` on any branch

**Risks**
- `!` `db.findUser` `this`-binding if not promisified correctly
- `?` whether cache/audit errors should route through `next(err)` (preserve existing behavior)
